    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-02-18T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-02-18T05:00:00-05:00" n="12"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d12">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00 R 29/492: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-02-18T10:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 18, 1921—10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 2:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>117. B–415. For Davis. Am instructing Smith withdraw from Austrian Section
                    contemporaneously our withdrawal Paris, Saturday morning. Following form: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I am instructed by my Government to announce the retirement of its
                            unofficial representatives upon the Reparation Commission. This decision
                            has been reached only after long hesitation and careful
                            consideration.</p>
                        <p>All representation upon the Commission was in the beginning unofficial in
                            anticipation of ratification of the Treaty of Versailles by the
                            signatory parties. Other powers have ratified and their representations
                            long ago became official. The United States has not ratified and as time
                            has passed its unofficial representation on the Commission has gradually
                            become anomalous.</p>
                        <p>My Government under the foregoing conditions has felt unable to cooperate
                            with the Allied Powders at Brussels and elsewhere in the preparation of
                            plans which seem to involve a change in the treaty. It realizes fully
                            the great difficulty of these problems and recognizes the value of
                            unified action, but as it cannot at present take part in such
                            discussions or even express any views upon the subjects discussed it
                            feels that it is undesirable to retain even unofficial representation on
                            the Commission likely to be charged with the execution of such
                            plans.</p>
                        <p>My Government instructs me further to express its sincere appreciation of
                            the many courtesies which the Commission and its members have shown the
                            United States and its unofficial representatives.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <list>
                            <item>Boyden</item>
                            <item>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace</hi>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
